title: For Sale:  Hi Standard Olympic ISU pistol, .22s, LH
location: Far NE IL, Illinois, United States
postcontent:
Hi Standard Olympic ISU pistol, left handed grip.

This is the improved version of the Hi Standard pistols that were winning guns at the Olympics.  There were only 3 US manufacturers whose handguns had Olympic gold medals. The first was at the the beginning of the modern Olympics in the 1800s, with the Colt military revolvers.  The S&W free pistol also was a winner in that category on one occasion.  Other than that, Hi Standard has been the only US gun with a win of that type.  

This model, the ISU, moves the muzzle brake into the barrel itself.  The guns used in Olympic competition were used without their add-on muzzle brakes ("stabilizers" in the old Hi Standard terminology) because these worsened the accuracy significantly.

This gun also has vents along the length of the barrel.  Trigger pull weight is adjustable.

One magazine included.  No box or papers.

This is NOT an NIB or "perfect mint" collector's gun, and has been used in competition and related activities.  There is some finish wear, the grip shows age from hand contact, and there are a few tiny areas of loss in blueing.  Also, no box or papers, and only one magazine.  It has both German proof marks and US re-import markings.  The barrel has upper ports, which are not common in the US-sale guns.

FFL transfer only, even for IL FOID permit holders.

Although considered a competition gun, these guns are superb for defense and protection use due to their extreme accuracy, rapid fire capability (5 rounds per second with precise accuracy), and very low bullet penetration into secondary objects or unintended targets.

Additional images on request.  Offers considered.

Hi Standard (Hamden, Hartford) and High Standard (TX) Victors also available.  

This gun is one of several target and "other use" pistols available, which are NOT listed on Armslist.  For a complete list and EXPERT'S SELECTION GUIDE to these guns, please email.  The guide and list are free.

Prices on the Victors range from the $500 range (TX, in box and excellent) to around $1000 (Hamden, steel rib, with weights), and stuff in between.

1911-A1 CAL .45

title: For Sale:  FP6 H&K 12ga Shotgun
postcontent:
This item has only been used twice, it's in perfect condition. The smoothest pump action you will ever feel!

Taken from Wikipedia: 

The Heckler & Koch Fabarm FP6 is a pump-action combat shotgun that was manufactured by the Italian firearms company Fabbrica Bresciana Armi S.p.A. (FABARM) and merchandised by Heckler & Koch. It was intended for civilian and law enforcement use.

The machined receiver is manufactured from lightweight Ergal 55 alloy and is drilled and tapped for scope mounting. Three of the four variants were sold with an attached Picatinny rail for mounting optics or accessories and the bottom forward edge of the forend is also drilled to accept an accessory rail. With the exception of the short-barreled model, FABARM shotguns are sold with their Tribore barrel which is a deep-drilled, machined barrel with three separate internal bore profiles. Beginning at the chamber and forcing cone, the bore is enlarged to .7401" to soften recoil while the second profile is in the middle of the barrel gradually choking down to .7244" to emulate a cylinder bore profile to increase velocity. The final bore is the FABARM choke system which consists of standard choking followed by a cylinder profile at the muzzle which serves to improve shot patterns and distribution.[3] The muzzle is threaded to accept one of five different chokes or a muzzle brake/compensator. Some models were sold with a ventilated barrel shroud.

Features of the weapon include a chrome-plated trigger, slide release, and shell carrier. There is also an oversized triangular push-button safety. The trigger group is held in the receiver by two pins which makes removal for cleaning and maintenance very easy. Some models have a flip-up frontsight (which serves as a low-profile sight when closed) while others have a small blade sight. Other models were issued with ghost-ring sights.[1]

The forend and buttstock are synthetic black polymer with the latter having a synthetic rubber recoil pad mounted on the end. One model was issued instead with a heavy wire gauge folding stock and pistol grip. Models were available with either a black anodized protective finish, matte finish, or were finished in carbon fiber.

title: For Trade:  FT/FS - Stoeger Cougar 9 and Taurus PT145 Millenium Pro
postcontent:
Hello - I've got both a Stoeger Cougar 9 - blue with wood grips in 9mm.  Comes with Original case and all original accessories and two clips.  I really enjoy firing this guy and for those who enjoy light recoil, cheap ammo and fun the range this guy not only looks classy but also feels it at the range.  It's a perfect home defense weapon and a real joy to shoot.  I've owned Beretta's version (the 8000) and I must say I can't tell the difference between the two except I get a little better accuracy out of the Stoeger.  I mostly attribute this to being a later model and improved sights however could also be that I'm a more experienced shooter as well.  Nevertheless for the money - it's looks, accuracy and feel are hard to beat.  I've added a brief review below.

http://www.handgunsmag.com/handguns/stoeger-cougar-compact/

Also - I have a Taurus Millenium Pro PT145 in black .45 ACP.  She's a subcompact .45 at about 3" and is an excellent choice for those who want stopping power, concealment and a cost effective solution.  I won't rant and rave over it's accuracy as to be honest I haven't shot it much being that the .45 ACP round is fairly expensive to practice with at the range.  However, I will only say that I haven't had a single FTF, FTE or FTFd over the 200 rounds and several years of ownership.  She simply eats everything I've put in it and asks for more.  You again really couldn't ask for a better gun for the money.  While looking fairly plain she does look pretty nice too considering the price.  Also included is a link below for the search handicapped:

http://www.firearmstalk.com/forums/f15/your-thoughts-taurus-pt145-millennium-pro-70913/

Now for a quick FAQ:

Why are you selling?  ~ Simply put, I have over a dozen handguns in various calibers and don't have a single shotgun currently.  I'm not interested in a $1k shotgun and most my other pistols are $1k plus therefore it seems the most rational choice to offer up a trade in the $3-7 range to acquire one.  Also - being that I have quite a few semi auto's in the $1k and above range I have little money left for additional toys unless I'm looking for a divorce and even then it will likely cost me more.  :)

What are you interested in for TRADE?  ~ I'd entertain almost any SHOTGUN or REVOLVER in the $3-7 range for either one or both the aforementioned firearms up for trade.  I'm not afraid to add money or to receive it for various trades so don't hesitate to throw something out there.  Worst either can say is no.  I don't have a shotgun or a revolver and am interested in both.  Nothing in .22 please unless it's a Walther P22.

What are you asking for both?  ~ That's subjective however I'm very fair with all trades and don't want any more than a reasonable person is asking.  If you are looking for $500 for your trade citing another website for that price I'll generally apply the same website as a good reference for mine.  Please keep it honest and real as that is my full intention as well.

Where are you located and how far are you willing to travel?  ~ I am located in the North Fort Worth region near 820W/N.  I'm willing to travel 30 min in any direction for the right trade.  No shipping as it defeats the purpose for me.  I can walk down to Cabella's and trade in both guns to get a Mossberg 500.  I'm looking for a like minded individual as if we are to survive this fun game of trying out other guns we should stick together right?  Not to mention save money.

Any requirements?  ~ Yes, follow the law.  Nothing more or less.  FTF only and bill of sale is a MUST.  It protects both parties and again ensures Texas law is followed accordingly.  Any additional questions please don't hesitate to contact me.

"The [DP-51] is a compact, lightweight pistol with an unconventional trigger mechanism called "fast action". The frame is composed of an aluminum alloy with a matte finish, while the slide is of blued steel.

The "fast action" trigger mechanism allows the hammer to be decocked while still keeping the mainspring compressed. A light pull on the trigger causes the hammer to flick back, after which the pistol would behave in conventional single-action (SA) mode.

The pistol can also be fired in conventional single- and double-action (DA) modes. The "fast action" mode allows the trigger travel of DA mode and the trigger weight of SA mode. This allows a more accurate first shot due to the lighter weight of the trigger. It is also safer due to the longer trigger travel required to fire the pistol. The factory magazines hold 13 rounds. Smith & Wesson 59-series magazines are compatible with the DP51 but will protrude slightly.

The pistol also has an ambidextrous safety and three-dot sights. It is also equipped with a firing pin block which (as its name implies) blocks the firing pin from moving forward unless the trigger is pulled."

The PCR name stands for ‘Police Czech Republic,’ the group for whom the model was originally designed. Nearly identical in size to the CZ 75 Compact, it weighs in at a full 1/4 pound lighter owing to its forged aluminum frame, making it more comfortable for everyday carry.

Equipped with a decocking lever, the PCR is designed to be decocked before holstering. After decocking, the trigger safety is much like that of a double action revolver. While there is no need to flip a safety lever off, the relatively longer and heavier trigger pull for the first round requires the conscious decision to pull the trigger before firing. Other additions to the PCR include rubber grip panels, serrated front and back straps for improved handling and a loaded chamber indicator.

He planned and conducted a broad range of special operations missions covering the entire operational continuum. These missions gave the President of the United States an option when overt military and / or diplomatic actions were not viable or politically feasible. He was also a member of a U.S. State Department close protection team assigned to several high profile government officials and visiting diplomats in Israel. He has extensive experience and training in fully armored vehicle operations, advance team operations, motorcade operations, CAT (Counter Assault Team) operations and surveillance/counter surveillance operations.
